<section xml:id="lesson5_5" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Combining Gates in Vector Notation </title>

  <subsection xml:id="sec_qops_in_parallel" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Combining Quantum Operations in Parallel</title>
    <p> Let's consider the following scenario. Suppose we have a 2-qubit state, but we only want to
      apply a gate to one of the qubits. Or, what if we want to apply two separate 1-qubit gates to
      the two qubits. How would we do so, in a general way? As far as we know, a 2-qubit state
      (represented by a <m>4 \times 1</m> vector) needs a 2-qubit gate (represented by a <m>4 \times 4</m> matrix) to
      operate on it. What can we do here? </p>

    <p> As it turns out, vector notation gives us an incredibly convenient way of handling this
      case: combining quantum operations that occur in parallel. If you recall, the method we used
      to <term>tensor product</term> on the two states. Thanks to the magic of vector notation, the
      process to combine quantum operations involve performing the tensor product of the two
      operations! </p>

    <p>
      <term>More to come soon...</term>
    </p>

